		<item>
		<title>3 Key Questions to Determine if Performance Max Is Right for You</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/05/01/is-performance-max-right-for-you</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Navah Hopkins]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 01 May 2023 13:30:29 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=69586</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Learn how to examine your budget, campaign types, and assets to make the right decision for your account!</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/05/01/is-performance-max-right-for-you">3 Key Questions to Determine if Performance Max Is Right for You</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Performance Max (PMax) launched at <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/06/14/google-marketing-livestream-2021">Google Marketing Live (GML) 2021</a> and has received a mixed response. Some see great results and others struggle with the mixed-bag performance caused by lack of control.</p>
<p>Understanding whether PMax will serve your account well comes down to these core criteria:</p>
<ul>
<li>What is your budget?</li>
<li>Are your individual channels performing well?</li>
<li>Can you provide all creative assets?</li>
</ul>
<p>While there isn‚Äôt a definitive yes or no, these questions can help you forecast PMax‚Äôs success for your brand. Before we dive into those questions, let&#8217;s do a brief overview of this campaign type.</p>
<h2>What is Performance Max?</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/google-ads-performance-max-pre-launch-optimizations">Performance Max campaigns</a> cover all <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/05/types-of-google-ads">Google Ads types</a> (except Local Service Ads), allocating budget and creative where the algorithm thinks it can do the most good for your marketing objectives. This means that instead of running Search, Display, Video, Discover, Local, or Shopping campaigns separately, you have a single campaign/budget covering all of those channels.</p>
<p>Currently, exclusions require you to work with your Google rep, which means the out-of-the-box campaign doesn‚Äôt allow for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/06/06/negative-keyword-guide">negative keywords</a>.</p>
<p>These campaigns require text and visual creative. If you don‚Äôt supply your own creative (images and videos) Google will create them for you. These creatives typically don‚Äôt perform as well so it‚Äôs important you have visual creatives ready.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/google-marketing-live-2021-performance-max-setup.jpg" alt="google marketing live performance max set up" width="706" height="597" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-71339" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/google-marketing-live-2021-performance-max-setup.jpg 706w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/google-marketing-live-2021-performance-max-setup-480x406.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 706px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>How to determine whether PMax is right for you</h2>
<p>Making the right decision on whether or not to run a Performance Max campaign comes down to three things: budget, existing campaigns, and creative.</p>
<h3>What is your budget?</h3>
<p>All <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/29/ad-channels">ad channels</a> have different auction prices. Depending on your budget, you may or may not be able to lean into a channel that would serve you well. As a general rule of thumb, your budgets should allow for at least one <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/10/25/lead-qualification">qualified lead or sale</a> per day. If your budget can‚Äôt support enough clicks to lead to that, you‚Äôll be left with the following options:</p>
<ul>
<li>Raise your budget so you can achieve enough clicks per day.</li>
<li>Adjust your targets/keywords so you‚Äôre not entering expensive auctions.</li>
<li>Abandon the channel and go for a different one.</li>
</ul>
<p>For constrained budgets, visually-oriented placements like display and video are typically cheaper than spots on the SERP (search engine result page). By using PMax, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/01/19/google-ads-for-small-businesses">smaller budgets</a> can snag bargain placements that would otherwise not be achievable.</p>
<p>Bigger budgets can succeed with PMax as well, but PMax can become a bit of a black box for budget allocation, and you also may need to pause your other channels.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/performance-max-right-for-you-budget-allocation.png" alt="performance max right for you - budget allocation" width="720" height="335" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-70851" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/performance-max-right-for-you-budget-allocation.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/performance-max-right-for-you-budget-allocation-480x223.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://twitter.com/MenachemAni/status/1550157222684119041" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Image source</a> </em></p>
<h3>How are your other channels performing?</h3>
<p>All Google Ads channels can empower each other. Paid search can only pick up <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/06/30/commercial-intent-keywords">transactional traffic</a> if your prospects know to search for what you offer. Brand sentiment alone cannot drive sales if your beloved followers can‚Äôt find you. Investing in PMax will ensure your bases are covered, but that also means leaving existing campaigns behind.</p>
<p>If your search campaigns are doing well, layering in PMax could potentially steal traffic. Additionally, if you‚Äôre running <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2013/03/19/why-bid-on-branded-terms-ppc">branded campaigns</a> to protect your brand (and your other campaigns from false positives), PMax might duplicate those efforts.</p>
<p>However, if you‚Äôre struggling to afford the auction prices for Google Search, PMax can be a hero.</p>
<p>The biggest risk for cannibalization is YouTube. <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/03/how-to-advertise-on-youtube">Youtube campaigns</a> allow for much more control over the pacing of creative and targeting. If your Youtube campaigns are performing, absolutely consider holding on PMax unless all other channels are struggling.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/performance-max-campaign-cannibalization.png" alt="performance max right for you - campaign priority" width="720" height="358" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-70852" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/performance-max-campaign-cannibalization.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/performance-max-campaign-cannibalization-480x239.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/my-two-cents-performance-max-campaigns-alex-van-de-pol/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Image source</a> </em></p>
<h3>Can you supply all the creative?</h3>
<p>PMax is often referred to as a black box campaign because there isn‚Äôt as much data on the specific queries or placements. However, this encourages advertisers to focus on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/11/21/customer-journey-mapping">message mapping</a> creative. Honing the audience signals and creative assets matters more for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/01/23/optimize-performance-max-campaigns">optimizing your Performance Max campaigns</a> than negative keywords and placements.</p>
<p>With that in mind, it‚Äôs vital that any PMax campaigns have visual creative assets. This includes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Images that will work for all Display and Google Discover spots</li>
<li>Video ads for 15 and 30-second spots</li>
<li>High-resolution logos</li>
</ul>
<p>If you‚Äôre not able to provide all the creative, Performance Max might not convert as well as standalone campaigns. You can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/05/performance-max-tips">learn more things to know before you start a Performance Max campaign here</a>.</p>
<h2>There&#8217;s only one way to find out if Performance Max is right for you</h2>
<p>Google Ads Performance Max campaigns can be a powerful profit generator for brands with rich visual creative and a clear understanding of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/07/16/engagement-ads">who their target market is</a>. There is no concrete answer on whether PMax will work for your brand‚Äîit&#8217;s not without its <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/20/performance-max-pros-cons">pros, cons, and polarized perspectives</a>.</p>
<p>The best way to know is to test while ensuring you‚Äôre not running redundant campaigns. Consider pausing standalone campaigns while running PMax so there‚Äôs no cannibalization of budget.</p>
<p>If PMax outperforms the standalone campaigns, you can free yourself from micromanaging lots of campaigns, focusing on creative and audiences. Should PMax underperform, you‚Äôll still have your standalone campaigns and won‚Äôt have the pressure to come up with creative for channels you didn‚Äôt intend to run.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/05/01/is-performance-max-right-for-you">3 Key Questions to Determine if Performance Max Is Right for You</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>How to Scale Success in Google Ads (&#038; More Importantly, When)</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/04/04/how-to-scale-success-in-google-ads</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Navah Hopkins]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 04 Apr 2023 13:30:36 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Google Ads]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=70841</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Learn not only *how* to scale successful ad creative and ad strategies, but also *when*‚Äîlest it backfire on you!</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/04/04/how-to-scale-success-in-google-ads">How to Scale Success in Google Ads (&#038; More Importantly, When)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Most Google Ad strategies and tips revolve around improving failing accounts, but there‚Äôs plenty of opportunity to grow and unlock profit when your accounts are performing well, too. That&#8217;s why it&#8217;s important to know when your account is ready for scale and when it would make sense to hold steady‚Äîas attempting to scale prematurely can actually backfire on you.</p>
<p>Every account is different and timelines for scale should correlate to spend, so in this post, I&#8217;m going to share with you:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#ready">How to tell if your Google Ads account is ready for scaling</a></li>
<li><a href="#creative">How to scale successful creative</a></li>
<li><a href="#strategies">How to scale successful strategies</a></li>
</ul>
<p>Let&#8217;s get started.</p>
<div id="ready"></div>
<h2>How to tell if your Google Ads account is ready to scale</h2>
<p>Before applying any scaling strategies, it‚Äôs vital to ensure your account is ready for them. As a general rule, your Google Ads account should:</p>
<ul>
<li>Consistently meet<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/11/07/how-to-lower-cost-per-lead-google-ads"> cost per acquisition (CPA)</a> and return on ad spend (ROAS) goals, with <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/02/08/google-ads-conversion-tracking-mistakes">trustworthy conversion tracking</a>.</li>
<li>Consistently spend campaign budget.</li>
<li>Meet lead/sales quality standards.</li>
<li>Have clear buyer personas and ad creative/audience targeting optimized.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/target-market-vs-target-audience-vs-persona.png" alt="target market vs target audience" width="720" height="489" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-61299" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/target-market-vs-target-audience-vs-persona.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/target-market-vs-target-audience-vs-persona-480x326.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Additional positive signs include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Above 50% <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/07/26/search-impression-share">impression share</a> and the majority of the lost impression share is lost to budget.</li>
<li>Good or better ad rating correlating with real-world performance.</li>
<li>Campaigns have been out of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/09/13/learning-period">learning phase</a> for more than 14 days.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/google-ads-learning-period-2.png" alt="" width="237" height="130" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-15889" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/google-ads-learning-period-2.png 237w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/google-ads-learning-period-2-100x55.png 100w" sizes="(max-width: 237px) 100vw, 237px" /></p>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/02/08/google-ads-conversion-tracking-mistakes">Trusting conversion tracking</a> and being able to draw direct lines to profit are a must before you think about scale. While there is no hard and fast timeline, you‚Äôll want to make sure any of your optimization initiatives have at least a quarter to prove themselves out.</p>
<div id="creative"></div>
<h2>How to scale successful creative</h2>
<p>When you know you have winning creative, it‚Äôs natural to want to get the most mileage out of it and apply it in multiple ways, such as by creating new campaigns with it or testing out ‚Äúspinoff‚Äù variants of that creative.</p>
<p>For example, if you‚Äôre running visual creative (<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/05/23/google-display-ads">display ads</a>, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/13/video-ad-tools">video ads</a>, etc), and seeing conversions, you may decide you want to put those landing pages/creative ideas in your search campaigns. You could do this by creating new assets (<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/16/google-ads-extensions-now-assets">formerly known as extensions</a>) or creating entirely new responsive search ads. As a general rule with visual creative, you‚Äôll want to see:</p>
<ul>
<li>High video completion rate (30% &gt;)</li>
<li>High view-through conversion rate and/or assisted conversions</li>
<li>Landing page visits</li>
</ul>
<p>Translating visual creative into assets or search ads means taking the core theme and expressing it within the character limit. For example, this video ad does a great job of putting the brand and product front and center. It also doesn‚Äôt push the sale, relying on cheeky language over ‚Äútry‚Äù/‚Äùdemo‚Äù language.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/scale-google-ads-youtube-ad-example.png" alt="how to scale google ads - example of good youtube ad" width="720" height="379" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-70844" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/scale-google-ads-youtube-ad-example.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/scale-google-ads-youtube-ad-example-480x253.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Translating this ad into a text ad or assets would mean:</p>
<ul>
<li>Using sitelink and price extensions to promote specific variants.</li>
<li>Leaning into the ‚Äúprivate parts‚Äù language as it‚Äôs acceptable for Google and conveys the brand tone.</li>
<li>Honoring that the user may have seen the ad before using YouTube <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/21/google-ads-audience-targeting-cheat-sheet">audience targeting</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Here‚Äôs the text ad Lume is currently running for the query, ‚Äúnatural deodorant for women:‚Äù</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/scale-google-ads-lume-text-ad-example.png" alt="how to scale google ads - example of text ad" width="720" height="200" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-70843" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/scale-google-ads-lume-text-ad-example.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/scale-google-ads-lume-text-ad-example-480x133.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/24/google-ads-examples"><em>More great text ad examples here</em></a>.</p>
<p>Just like visual ads can be converted to text, so too can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/03/how-to-write-exceptional-ppc-ad-copy">great text ads</a> be converted to visual. Taking the core messaging of a text ad and translating it into visuals might seem trickier, but it really relies on the following:</p>
<ul>
<li>Knowing your audience and what will grab their attention.</li>
<li>Using the visual (and potentially audio) medium to their fullest.</li>
<li>Maintaining the core tone and language of the text ad.</li>
</ul>
<p>Whether you use single creative campaigns or <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/07/05/performance-max-tips">Performance Max</a>, leveraging different creative types to communicate with your prospects can help you reach more of your market.</p>
<p><span><div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4b0.png" alt="üí∞" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> <strong>Ready to hit the jackpot of great ad copywriting? </strong></span></p>
<p><strong>Free guide: <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSContentDLWebBlogInContentTextLinkTrickstoClicks.html?cid=Web_Blog_InContent_TextLink_TrickstoClicks_Download" class="waffle-rich-text-link">10 Tricks to Get the Click: How to Write Exceptional PPC Ad Copy (with Examples!)</a></strong><span></div></div></span></p>
<div id="strategies"></div>
<h2>How to scale successful strategies</h2>
<p>There are many paths to successful campaigns. Knowing that you have a proven <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/10/google-ads-account-structure">account structure</a> can help build confidence to invest in more markets.</p>
<p>Typically in search campaigns, accounts will have one of the following strategies:</p>
<ul>
<li>Markets as the campaign and services/products as the ad groups.</li>
<li>Services/products as the campaign and different personas as the ad groups.</li>
<li>Auction price/customer value as the campaign and the products/services as ad groups.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/google-ads-account-structure-right-roofing.png" alt="google ads account structure - roofing account example" width="720" height="369" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60973" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/google-ads-account-structure-right-roofing.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/google-ads-account-structure-right-roofing-480x246.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>The best structure choice for you will depend on the complexity of the offering, your budget, as well as your desired ramp-up pace.</p>
<p>Once you find the right structure for your campaigns, you can begin applying it to more markets/initiatives.</p>
<p>As a general rule, pick one part of your business to prove out which structure you‚Äôll be testing. Give it at least 30-60 days of optimization time to ensure you‚Äôre on the right track to roll it out to the rest of your business.</p>
<p><span><div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/2734.png" alt="‚ú¥" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Free guide: </span></p>
<p><a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLAccountStructure.html?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_LastAccountStructureGuide_Download" class="waffle-rich-text-link">The Last Guide to Google Ads Account Structure You&#8217;ll Ever Need</a><span> </span></p>
<p><span></div></div></span></p>
<h2>Be smart about scaling your Google Ads</h2>
<p>Scaling Google Ad campaigns is equal parts reliant on subjective and objective signals. Knowing that creative or structures are meeting metric goals is absolutely a sign it&#8217;s time to scale. There‚Äôs also factoring in timing. Scale should only happen when no operational change can support it.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/04/04/how-to-scale-success-in-google-ads">How to Scale Success in Google Ads (&#038; More Importantly, When)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
