		<item>
		<title>Why Your Non-Ecommerce Business Should Set Conversion Values (&#038; How to Do It)</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/10/how-to-determine-conversion-value</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Navah Hopkins]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 11 Oct 2022 01:38:55 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=65294</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Uncover the key to how to improving lead quality and securing the highest ROI in Google Ads (and other platforms). </p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/10/how-to-determine-conversion-value">Why Your Non-Ecommerce Business Should Set Conversion Values (&#038; How to Do It)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The days of just using individual conversions are long past. All ad platforms now encourage advertisers to embrace and leverage conversion values. Take Google Ads, for example: Max conversion value is one of the only bidding options for PMax campaigns and has been getting a lot of love in account recommendations.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/maximize-conversion-value-google-ads-bidding.png" alt="maximize conversion value bidding in google ads" width="568" height="371" class="wp-image-65325 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/maximize-conversion-value-google-ads-bidding.png 568w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/maximize-conversion-value-google-ads-bidding-480x313.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 568px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>If you‚Äôre in ecommerce, conversion value is nothing new‚Äîrevenue tracking is at the heart of successful shopping campaigns. However, if you‚Äôre in a services industry or one that doesn‚Äôt have a set price per engagement, you might struggle to land on a conversion value.</p>
<p>In this post we‚Äôll dive into how to do that. Here&#8217;s what we&#8217;ll cover:</p>
<ul>
<li>The difference between individual conversions and conversion values.</li>
<li>The benefits of leaning into conversion values.</li>
<li>How to come up with a conversion value.</li>
</ul>
<p>Note that this post will be heavily focused on how Google leverages conversion values, however, the lessons learned can be applied to other channels.</p>
<h2>What‚Äôs the difference between conversions and conversion values?</h2>
<p>A conversion is any action you ask an ad platform to track. Conversion actions can range from those on the path to profit (downloading a guide, making a call, etc.), to the completed sale.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-conversion-actions.png" alt="google ads conversion action setup" width="600" height="658" class="size-full wp-image-65297 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-conversion-actions.png 600w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-conversion-actions-480x526.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 600px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/09/25/conversion-value">Conversion values</a> are the monetary amount you tell the ad platform to attribute to the completed action.</p>
<p>For example, I might set a conversion action to track all phone calls stemming from my Google Ads ads. Google will track each of them as long as I set the action to a primary action. Whether it values those calls at $1 or $100 or any other amount depends on me adding the conversion value into the action.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-conversion-action-details-conversion-value.png" alt="google ads conversion value" width="720" height="409" class="size-full wp-image-65296 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-conversion-action-details-conversion-value.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-ads-conversion-action-details-conversion-value-480x273.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>In short, you can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/30/google-ads-conversion-tracking">track conversions in Google Ads</a> without conversion values‚Äîhowever, you are creating data weaknesses for the ad platform as well as internal reporting.</p>
<h2>Why should non-ecommerce businesses set conversion values?</h2>
<p>One of the biggest false positives/negatives in <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/09/07/ppc-reporting">PPC reporting</a> is CPA (cost per acquisition). While a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/cost-per-action">low CPA</a> is a good thing, businesses will often over-fixate on getting that number as low as possible without factoring in the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/04/08/lead-quality">value of the leads</a> they‚Äôre getting.</p>
<p>ROAS (return on ad spend) is a more helpful <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/10/19/ppc-metrics">PPC metric</a> than CPA in knowing whether your ad campaigns are delivering real-world value.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/cpa-vs-roas.png" alt="cost per action vs return on ad spend" width="720" height="386" class="size-full wp-image-65322 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/cpa-vs-roas.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/cpa-vs-roas-480x257.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Conversion values help elevate the conversation and bring transparency to the true ROI on your ad spend. By setting conversion values, you‚Äôre helping Google Ads know which actions you value most and where to invest the budget.</p>
<p>Additionally, factoring in conversion values will help Google come up with more realistic forecasts on what additional investment could yield. This is especially useful if you have campaigns that are getting limited by budget but are bringing in low-value leads. By building in conversion values, Google can become more intelligent about <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/09/21/google-ads-audience-targeting-cheat-sheet">targeting your ideal prospects</a>.</p>
<h2>How to calculate conversion values when you&#8217;re not ecommerce</h2>
<p>Just because we‚Äôre bought into using conversion values doesn‚Äôt mean they‚Äôre straightforward. Unless you‚Äôre in a transactional industry like ecommerce, your conversion values will be based on models and data-backed best guesses.</p>
<p>A really useful place to begin is phone leads vs form-fills vs chats.</p>
<ul>
<li>If your sales team is best served by real-time interactions, phone leads might be your best lead type.</li>
<li>If it‚Äôs served best by lots of information about the prospect (potentially gained through a bit of content, a form, or other method), you might value your form-fills or chats higher.</li>
</ul>
<p>Regardless of which is the most useful, here&#8217;s what to do:</p>
<ol>
<li>Calculate your baseline value (you can adjust this as you operate and see real-world conversions) as 10% of your gross profit from the average engagement.</li>
<li>Use the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/03/improve-conversion-rates">conversion rates</a> from each lead type to come up with the conversion value.</li>
</ol>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><p>For example, let&#8217;s say I‚Äôm a lawyer, my average case is worth $6500, and my phone leads convert at 50% while form-fills convert at 20%.</p>
<ol>
<li>Baseline value per lead is $6,500 x 0.10 = $650</li>
<li>Phone lead conversion value = $650 x 0.50 = $325
Form fill conversion value = $650 x 0.20 = $130</li>
</ol></div></div>
<p>Be sure to also factor in location. Certain locations might be tougher/easier to service than others. If your margins are impacted by where a customer is based, or if you have insights about retention from certain markets, you may decide to value leads coming from certain regions higher or lower. This can be done through bid adjustments as well as excluding locations from high-value campaigns with higher ROAS goals.</p>
<h2>Know what your conversions are worth</h2>
<p>While it‚Äôs not mandatory to use conversion values, they will improve account performance if done correctly (and<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/02/21/google-ads-not-converting"> if you&#8217;re not seeing any conversions in your Google Ads, head to this post</a>). Take the time to audit your lead sources and see where your best leads come from. By valuing them higher than the average lead, you will help Google send you the best prospects and have the best chance for ROI.</p>
<p>For more ways to improve your account performance, use our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader"><strong>free Google Ads Performance Grader</strong></a>.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/10/10/how-to-determine-conversion-value">Why Your Non-Ecommerce Business Should Set Conversion Values (&#038; How to Do It)</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>Privacy-First Facebook Ad Targeting: 3 Creative (But Compliant) Workarounds</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/31/facebook-audience-targeting</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Navah Hopkins]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 31 Aug 2022 12:53:49 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Facebook Ads]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Social Media]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=63956</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>With a little creativity (and tracking code), you can effectively target ads on Facebook in a privacy-compliant way.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/31/facebook-audience-targeting">Privacy-First Facebook Ad Targeting: 3 Creative (But Compliant) Workarounds</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Facebook is a viable ad network for most advertisers, supporting ecommerce and lead gen businesses alike and helping both B2B and B2C own their customer journey.</p>
<p>But between increasing pressure from privacy compliance and updates forcing more conversion modeling, the targeting options from the early days just aren‚Äôt there anymore. We can‚Äôt rely purely on native audiences like we once could.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-ads-detailed-targeting.png" alt="facebook ads detailed targeting" width="720" height="288" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-64092" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-ads-detailed-targeting.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-ads-detailed-targeting-480x192.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>This leaves us with two options:</p>
<ol>
<li>Own that there will be more waste in our Facebook ad spend and build that into our marketing plans, or</li>
<li>Get creative.</li>
</ol>
<ul></ul>
<p>In this post, I&#8217;m going to show you how to get creative‚Äîwith three easy hacks to set up effective, privacy-compliant Facebook audiences.</p>
<h2>Hack #1: Create content-specific audiences with UTMs</h2>
<p>This first tip is from the amazing Michele Morgan (who offers even more <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/resources/facebook-ad-targeting">privacy-friendly Facebook targeting options here</a>). UTM parameters are customizable snippets you can add on to the URLs your ads are pointing to, to track your campaigns&#8217; performance. They can be used to identify your traffic sources and which creatives are getting profitable engagements.</p>
<p>There are five UTM parameters you can add on to the end of the destination URL (<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/great-landing-pages">landing page</a>) in your ad:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Source </strong>is which website or channel you&#8217;re using (example: Facebook, Google, Email)</li>
<li><strong>Medium</strong> is the element within the source site (example: VideoAd, banner, newsletter)</li>
<li><strong>Campaign</strong> is whatever campaign, offer, or product you&#8217;re promoting with that medium (example: AprilPromo)</li>
<li><strong>Content </strong>can be used to identify which link was clicked if the medium has multiple links (example: Button, TextLink)</li>
<li><strong>Term </strong>is used to identify the keyword you&#8217;re targeting if a paid search ad (Example: Dress+Pants).</li>
</ul>
<p>For this hack, you&#8217;ll use a UTM to create audiences based on content users engage with. This will enable you to target categories that have been removed from Facebook native targeting.</p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><p><strong>It will look something like this:</strong></p>
<p>www.yourlandingpage.com?utm_source=facebook&amp;utm_medium=paid&amp;utm_campaign={{campaign.name}}&amp;utm_content={{adset.name}}&amp;utm_term={{ad.name}}</p></div></div>
<p>Before you stress about needing to do a bunch of additional work, remember that Facebook has a handy UTM builder in the ad builder interface.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-backup-audiences-url-parameters.png" alt="facebook ads UTM builder" width="612" height="802" class="wp-image-63958 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-backup-audiences-url-parameters.png 612w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-backup-audiences-url-parameters-480x629.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 612px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>Hack #2: Use in-market segments on other channels to build source audiences</h2>
<p>All too often, advertisers wait on installing tracking code until they start advertising on a channel.</p>
<p>Don&#8217;t.</p>
<p>By getting ahead and placing your code, you‚Äôll be able to start building source audiences for future lookalike and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/03/17/retargeting-campaign-tips">retargeting campaigns</a>‚Äîwhich is what this workaround is about.</p>
<p>Both <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/06/17/in-market-audiences">Google‚Äôs in-market audiences</a> and Microsoft‚Äôs Audience Network can help you to build these source audiences.</p>
<h3>Google in-market segments</h3>
<p>Google allows for the following transactional segments that are a little more restricted on Facebook:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Employment</strong>: <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/11/16/facebook-ad-not-approved">Facebook will disapprove ads</a> that try to use targeting when focusing on employment. The exception to this is on custom audiences (i.e. folks who have consented to be tracked/targeted by you). Using Google‚Äôs in-market and life events audience segments, you‚Äôll be able to build a traffic list that can then be turned into a remarketing or lookalike list.</li>
<li><strong>Real Estate</strong>: Like employment, Facebook considers real estate a special interest category. Often ads get accidentally tagged in this category due to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/02/07/facebook-ad-copy-examples">ad copy</a> or <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/06/24/design-facebook-ads-free">creative</a>. Using the residential and commercial in-market segment can help curate your Facebook and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/02/08/instagram-ads-cost">Instagram spend</a>.</li>
<li><strong>Finance:</strong> Facebook has been taking an increasingly critical eye on financial industries, which is why Google‚Äôs in-market audiences are so powerful. Audience segments focusing on credit monitoring and lending services are particularly powerful.</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/in-market-segments-google-ads.png" alt="google ads in-market segments" width="720" height="520" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-63960" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/in-market-segments-google-ads.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/in-market-segments-google-ads-480x347.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Keep in mind that using these segments still requires a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/03/30/cookie-consent-banner-examples">cookie compliance plan</a>. This data will only be useful if users are comfortable accepting tracking.</p>
<h3>Microsoft Audience Network</h3>
<p>Microsoft Ads has many of the same in-market and life event audiences. There are some that are specific to Microsoft Ads worth exploring:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Politics</strong>: Political ads face a lot of scrutiny and restriction and politics is one of the <a href="https://www.facebook.com/business/news/removing-certain-ad-targeting-options-and-expanding-our-ad-controls" target="_blank" rel="noopener">targeting options Facebook removed due to sensitivity</a>. Being able to build an interest audience through Microsoft Ads topic targeting is a powerful way to get more focused targeting.</li>
<li><strong>LinkedIn:</strong> While there is overlap with Google‚Äôs employment targeting, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/09/linkedin-audiences">Microsoft&#8217;s LinkedIn audience targeting</a> is a powerful way to prefilter spend. Whether you‚Äôre looking to target by company or by stage in the person‚Äôs career, these pre-qualifiers can help build a powerful remarketing or seed audience for Facebook.</li>
</ul>
<p>By using other channels to create audiences you‚Äôll be able to unlock this for yourself on Facebook as well as build in extra communication points with your clients.</p>
<div class='et-box et-shadow'>
					<div class='et-box-content'><p><strong><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4d7.png" alt="üìó" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Free guide <img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f4d7.png" alt="üìó" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> </strong></p>
<p><a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSLIQContentDLWebsiteFBAdTargeting.html?cid=Web_Any_ResourcesPage_FacebookAdTargetingStrategiesForPrivacy_Download">10 Facebook Ad Targeting Strategies That Work In a Privacy-First World</a></p></div></div>
<h2>Hack #3: Use greater than 1% lookalike audiences</h2>
<p>One of the big reasons advertisers stress over the loss of special interest audiences is the fear of relying on automation to uncover the right people. We want to be the ones in control. For example, when creating a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/facebook-lookalike-audiences">Facebook Lookalike Audience (LAL)</a>, we prefer to go with 1% (if you&#8217;re unfamiliar, the lower the percentage, the closer the match but the smaller the audience).</p>
<p>Yet by opting into the higher (and therefore looser lookalike percentages), we can pick up the audiences we lost without running afoul of the privacy-first web. The signals haven&#8217;t gone went away, they just can‚Äôt be actively targeted (here are more <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/target-audience-examples">target audience examples</a>).</p>
<p>Akvile Defazio recently Tweeted about this:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-backup-audiences-lookalikes.png" alt="akvile defazio tweet supporting 5% facebook lookalike audience" width="600" height="346" class="size-full wp-image-63959 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-backup-audiences-lookalikes.png 600w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/facebook-backup-audiences-lookalikes-480x277.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 600px, 100vw" /></p>
<blockquote><p><em>Not quite sure what it is about those Facebook 5% lookalike audiences, but they continue to perform super well and better than any other lower %s. </em></p>
<p><em>We love it, clients appreciate it, and our accounts benefit from it. If you aren&#8217;t testing higher LALs, I encourage you to do so.</em></p></blockquote>
<p>While this might seem like a ‚Äúgive up‚Äù strategy it‚Äôs really just adapting to the times. Ad platforms always bake more signals and values into their automated options than their manual ones. By allowing more automation and ceding some control, you can retain the bigger value add: targeting the right audience and achieving higher ROI.</p>
<h2>Try these privacy-first Facebook audience targeting workarounds</h2>
<p>Despite all of these <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/11/22/customer-data-privacy">customer data privacy</a> updates and changes, there are always paths forward to target your ideal prospects. By using other channels as well as leaning into automation, we can continue to get meaningful value out of Facebooks ads. To recap, here are the three hacks:</p>
<ol>
<li>Use UTMs to create content-based audiences</li>
<li>Use in-market segments on other channels (like search) to create source audiences for Facebook LAL/remarketing campaigns.</li>
<li>Try creating Facebook LAL audiences with a &gt;1% match.</li>
</ol>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/31/facebook-audience-targeting">Privacy-First Facebook Ad Targeting: 3 Creative (But Compliant) Workarounds</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>The Top 4 Online Advertising Channels: 12 Tips to Use Them Right</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/29/ad-channels</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Navah Hopkins]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 29 Jun 2022 14:40:12 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=62377</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>The rules of engagement for search, display, video, and social. Get 'em right!</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/29/ad-channels">The Top 4 Online Advertising Channels: 12 Tips to Use Them Right</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>All ad networks represent potential value for brands. Where they can fall short is if they are asked to do a job they‚Äôre not predisposed to do or behave the way other ad networks behave. Understanding the rules of engagement for each ad network can help you to assign them the right jobs, and more importantly, achieve the highest ROI.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ad-channel-roles.png" alt="ad channel roles" width="720" height="346" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62653" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ad-channel-roles.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/ad-channel-roles-480x231.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>This post is just going to focus on the four main ad channels:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Paid search:</strong> The Salesman</li>
<li><strong>Display:</strong> The Audience Builder</li>
<li><strong>Video:</strong> The Need Educator</li>
<li><strong>Paid social:</strong> The Impulse Enabler</li>
</ol>
<p>While each ad channel can do some of the others&#8217; jobs, they are best suited to their core function. Let&#8217;s take a look at each one and its core role, along with my top tips for getting the most out of each one.</p>
<h2>Paid search: The Salesman</h2>
<p>Paid search (usually <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/how-to-use-google-adwords">Google Ads</a>) is the default advertising channel for many brands. These are the ads served on the SERP (search engine results page). Google Search sees 5.6 billion searches per day, so it‚Äôs understandable brands want access to that visibility. Here are my top tips for using paid search right.</p>
<h3>Have a specific target in mind</h3>
<p>The nature of search means the person already knows what they need. They might be researching to decide which vendor makes the most sense, but for the most part, the product or service has already lodged itself in the user‚Äôs mind.<img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/search-ad-example.png" alt="search ad example" width="720" height="434" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62388" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/search-ad-example.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/search-ad-example-480x289.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>As such, paid search works best when you have a specific target market in mind for your products/services. You understand what those products and services are worth so you can set realistic goals for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/18/search-advertising-benchmarks">average cost per click</a> (CPC), cost per acquisition (CPA), and return on ad spend (ROAS).</p>
<h3>Choose the right keyword concepts</h3>
<p>Since paid search revolves around bidding on keyword concepts, you‚Äôll need to get into the mind of how your best customers search. Bidding on both ‚Äúattorney‚Äù and ‚Äúlawyer‚Äù will cause you to bid against yourself, and each has its own unique <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/02/14/how-does-google-ads-work">auction</a> price. By choosing the best keyword concept for your target market, you‚Äôll ensure you‚Äôre able to speak to your prospect in the way they want to be spoken to.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/free-keyword-tool-results.png" alt="free keyword tool results for attorney keywords" width="720" height="338" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62389" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/free-keyword-tool-results.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/free-keyword-tool-results-480x225.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Divide your headlines into hooks and CTAs</h3>
<p>Ads need to speak to user needs while also being more than keyword formulaic templates. A good way to think about paid search ads is dividing your headline ones into ‚Äúhooks‚Äùand your headline twos into calls to action (CTAs). Descriptions should include additional information the user might value knowing, but shouldn‚Äôt be mission-critical to getting their attention. Most users only read the headlines of ads.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/RSA-responsive-search-ad-headline-template.png" alt="responsive search ad headlines - template" width="720" height="165" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-59787" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/RSA-responsive-search-ad-headline-template.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/RSA-responsive-search-ad-headline-template-480x110.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/05/responsive-search-ad-copy"><em>Get our responsive search ad template here.</em></a></p>
<p>By harnessing the right keywords to target the right audience, search ads are powerful closers. You can use native audiences (in-market, affinity, etc.) or build their own through <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/04/12/first-party-data">first-party data</a> or using custom intent.</p>
<h2>Display: The Audience Builder</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/05/23/google-display-ads">Display campaigns</a> are far more valuable than &#8220;just <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/03/17/retargeting-campaign-tips">remarketing</a>‚Äù channels. They allow you to communicate with high-impact imagery as well as begin to build a curated audience for your other campaigns.</p>
<p>Display ads can be charged by CPM (cost per thousand users), CPC (cost per click), or CPA (cost per acquisition). Here are some tips for getting the most out of your display ads</p>
<h3>Conduct placement audits</h3>
<p>The key to activating display‚Äôs full value is <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/01/07/google-display-network-placements">placement</a> audits. Some placements will hold more value than others (and in turn have higher auction prices). It‚Äôs up to you to unpack whether a placement is worth the premium or not.</p>
<p>While most mobile app placements will be a waste (fat fingering an ad in the middle of a game is the worst kind of wasted spend), some can be useful. Make sure auditing placements is grounded in KPIs and strategic value.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/display-ad-placements.png" alt="display ad placement examples" width="499" height="434" class="aligncenter wp-image-62390" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://medium.com/inside-revenue/what-types-of-display-ads-should-you-run-part-3-35bee584c58c" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Image source</a></em></p>
<h3>Use them to prequalify your leads</h3>
<p>If you find that your<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/04/08/lead-quality"> lead quality has been poor</a>, display ads can be a powerful tool to reach your prospects while they‚Äôre researching their needs. You can help them understand if they‚Äôre thinking about value/quality the right way, or whether they should even be considering your product/service at all.</p>
<h3>Be creative with your creative</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/07/09/ad-design">Display ad creative</a> is far more important than it used to be. Users have gotten accustomed to beautiful creative, regardless of whether it‚Äôs sponsored. One of the ways Google and Microsoft lighten the load is with their Shutterstock integration. Whether you use Shutterstock or your own creative, you‚Äôll be able to get much more reach (and engagement) out of responsive display ads.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/display-ad-examples.png" alt="display ad examples on a hobby website" width="592" height="392" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62391" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/display-ad-examples.png 592w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/display-ad-examples-480x318.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 592px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Both <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/09/30/best-display-ad-examples">display ad examples</a> on this page have built-in buttons to signal the user to click. However, the World of Warcraft ad has better synergy with the topic of the page. While the Shopify Plus ad makes sense to serve to me (I‚Äôm an ideal target), interrupting my hobby time requires more creativity than a straightforward ad.</p>
<h2>Video: The Need Educator</h2>
<p>All ad networks have embraced video ads as a major creative type, and for good reason. <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/13/video-ad-tools">Video ad content</a> can inspire need through creative storytelling, alert a prospect on their eligibility to interact with products/services, and build positive sentiment toward a brand. Here are some key tips for creating<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/03/29/google-ads-video-campaign-settings"> video ad campaigns</a>.</p>
<h3>Prioritize the first 5 seconds</h3>
<p>The best video ads understand users likely won‚Äôt see past the first five seconds. While some lean into the six-second bumper ad format (equal part art and science), others attempt to persuade the user to stick around for the full ad.</p>
<p>Pragmatically, advertisers should focus on getting the following information out in the first five seconds:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/11/08/business-name-ideas">Business name</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/13/call-to-action-examples">Call to action</a></li>
<li>Contact method</li>
</ul>
<h3>Focus on your personas</h3>
<p>Video ads require strategic thinking on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/09/23/buyer-personas">target personas</a>. If you will be using real people, you need to make sure they match the target demographic you&#8217;re serving to. Using graphics can be a way around this‚Äîhowever, you need to make sure you maintain <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/07/31/brand-voice">brand voice</a> (i.e., if your brand isn‚Äôt cheeky in other content, you can‚Äôt suddenly have a cheeky cartoon ad).</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/youtube-ad-example.jpg" alt="skippable youtube ad example" width="720" height="469" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62393" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/youtube-ad-example.jpg 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/youtube-ad-example-480x313.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Set a frequency cap</h3>
<p>Aside from creative, it‚Äôs important to remember video ads interrupt content a user actively chose to engage in. If you serve the same ad (or ads in the same series) to people too frequently, they will eventually tune you out or develop bad brand sentiment. Be sure you set a frequency cap for daily/weekly views. A good place to start is five views per week and adjust from there.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/cap-frequency.png" alt="frequency cap setting" width="720" height="402" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62392" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/cap-frequency.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/cap-frequency-480x268.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>Paid social: The Impulse Enabler</h2>
<p>Paid social refers to ads on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/01/11/most-popular-social-media-platforms">social media platforms</a> like Facebook, Instagram, Twitter, LinkedIn, TikTok, etc.</p>
<h3>Regularly refresh your creative</h3>
<p>Your social ads require the biggest shift in strategy and creative from search. They revolve around new entities instead of old data, so you ened to refresh campaigns/ad sets/ads to help the algorithm continue to serve them optimally. There are plenty of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/06/24/design-facebook-ads-free">tools for designing Facebook ads</a>, like Canva.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/design-facebook-ad-creative-free-canva.png" alt="facebook ad templates in canva" width="720" height="364" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-50285" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/design-facebook-ad-creative-free-canva.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/design-facebook-ad-creative-free-canva-480x243.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>Be aware of privacy restrictions</h3>
<p>Building a good social campaign requires the most work in unpacking personas. Understanding who your people are and how to inspire their desire is key to winning at paid social. While this used to be child‚Äôs play with all the native targeting, privacy innovations have forced social ad networks to limit targeting and reporting options. For help in this arena, check out our resources:</p>
<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/09/13/facebook-ad-targeting-privacy-first-world">Facebook Ad Targeting in a Privacy-First World</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/11/11/facebook-advertising-strategies">7 Facebook Ad Strategies Working for Us, Post-iOS Update¬†</a></li>
<li><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/01/06/facebook-ads-on-platform-engagement">3 Lesser-Used Facebook Ad Strategies Making a Comeback</a></li>
</ul>
<h3>Use lookalike audiences</h3>
<p>Using customer lists to seed lookalikes has always been a part of social campaigns, and remains a viable way to focus budgets toward ideal prospects.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/facebook-audience-types.png" alt="facebook-audience-types" width="720" height="406" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-57046" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/facebook-audience-types.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/facebook-audience-types-480x271.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Conventional wisdom holds that 1% lookalike is the best setting, however, in more niche industries, 8% has been starting to perform better. Test both schools of thought to find the best audiences for you.</p>
<p>This means that creative is even more crucial than before. Segmenting out which creative will speak to the user relies on visual queues and demographic matching.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/facebook-ad-example-kiara.png" alt="facebook ad example" width="400" height="558" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-62394" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/facebook-ad-example-kiara.png 400w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/06/facebook-ad-example-kiara-215x300.png 215w" sizes="(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="https://www.facebook.com/ads/library/?active_status=all&amp;ad_type=all&amp;country=US&amp;view_all_page_id=107241124145440&amp;sort_data[direction]=desc&amp;sort_data[mode]=relevancy_monthly_grouped&amp;search_type=page&amp;media_type=all" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>View the ad example here.</em></a></p>
<p>This <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/11/14/facebook-video-ad">Facebook video ad</a> does a great job because it highlights various people using the product and also plays into the common obsession some people have with taking care of acne. There‚Äôs also a clear call to action (Shop Now) and a relatable <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/08/28/facebook-ad-headlines">headline</a>.</p>
<p>What makes this ad a great case study in impulse enablement is how applicable it is to a wide group, while also solving a relatable problem.</p>
<h2>Final tips &amp; takeaways</h2>
<p>Each of these¬†<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/02/10/paid-media-strategy">paid media</a> channels have a place in your marketing mix, and each has its own rules of engagement. Here are my two final takeaways for using these ad channels:</p>
<ul>
<li>Each channel also has certain budget thresholds for success. If you don‚Äôt have the budget for one, you might be able to get comparable value by leveraging another.</li>
<li>The best way to unify their efforts is to use analytics as your main source of truth and collaborate on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/22/cross-channel-marketing">cross-channel messaging</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>We can help you succeed on these ad channels. See our full range of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/marketing-services?cid=Web_WS_InContent_TextLink_Solutions_Marketing_Services_Demo">digital marketing solutions</a> to learn how.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/06/29/ad-channels">The Top 4 Online Advertising Channels: 12 Tips to Use Them Right</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
		<item>
		<title>The Super-Easy, 5-Question PPC Audit</title>
		<link>https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/16/ppc-audit</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Navah Hopkins]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 16 May 2022 14:56:54 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Paid Search Marketing]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://www.wordstream.com/?p=61100</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Get your account structure, conversion tracking, ad copy‚Äîand more‚Äîin top shape with these key considerations.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/16/ppc-audit">The Super-Easy, 5-Question PPC Audit</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Managing PPC accounts is a lot like playing a game: Once you understand the rules, you can start getting into creative strategy. Account audits are an important part of understanding the rules‚Äîessentially it&#8217;s getting the board ready to play.</p>
<p>While there are different checks to be done in a PPC audit‚Äîsome weekly, some even daily‚Äîmany of them can be boiled down to five key questions:</p>
<ol>
<li>Does your account structure support your business goals?</li>
<li>Do you trust your conversion tracking?</li>
<li>How well does your creative match your target persona?</li>
<li>Are you falling into accidental waste?</li>
<li>Should you be scaling or optimizing?</li>
</ol>
<p>In this post, I&#8217;m going to cover each of these questions and provide tips and rules of thumb to help you address each one. Each of these questions governs a different aspect of PPC management, all of which are applicable to any account. If you‚Äôre not asking them at least once per quarter, you‚Äôre doing your account a disservice.</p>
<h2>1. Does your account structure support your business goals?</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/10/google-ads-account-structure">Account structure</a> is arguably the most important element of an account. A poorly structured account will tank even the best creative and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/02/20/stop-burning-your-adwords-budget">waste valuable marketing dollars</a> and time.</p>
<p>For example, a common structural error is including too many ad groups in a campaign or too many keywords in an ad group. If a business needs to cover all services/markets/products, it‚Äôs understandable why there might be some overstuffing‚Äî but an ideal campaign should only have <strong>5-7 ad groups</strong> and no more than<strong> 3-5 keyword concepts</strong>. This is to ensure the budget can support each ad group and that the keywords are grouped by price and relevance.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/google-ads-account-structure-feature.png" alt="google ads account structure overview" width="700" height="507" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-61001" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/google-ads-account-structure-feature.png 700w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/google-ads-account-structure-feature-480x348.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 700px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Understanding which structure will serve you best comes down to the following business questions:</p>
<ul>
<li>How much is a customer worth?</li>
<li>Are all markets worth the same or are some more valuable?</li>
<li>Do you need to invest in all parts of your business, or can you play favorites?</li>
</ul>
<p>These questions will give context to the existing account setup as well as inform the best path forward</p>
<p>Also, <strong>campaigns should cover one country at most </strong>(ideally one timezone/major market). This is because ads serve in the timezone of the account, not the user. Additionally, it‚Äôs challenging for a single budget to support more than one major market. Use Impression Share (and impression share lost to budget) to guide you on if you‚Äôre asking your budget to handle too much.</p>
<p>In some cases, there might not be enough budget to go after all the parts of the business. <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/07/01/dynamic-search-ads">Dynamic Search Ads</a> (DSAs) can be a powerful way to cover multiple parts of the business.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-dynamic-search-ads.png" alt="dynamic search ad setup in google ads" width="1198" height="904" class="aligncenter wp-image-61106" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-dynamic-search-ads.png 1198w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-dynamic-search-ads-980x739.png 980w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-dynamic-search-ads-480x362.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 980px) 980px, (min-width: 981px) 1198px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>However, DSAs can also steal budget from general search ad groups/campaigns if negatives aren‚Äôt set correctly.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-dynamic-vs-regular.png" alt="analytics showing both a dynamic and regular ad struggling" width="720" height="148" class="aligncenter wp-image-61105 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-dynamic-vs-regular.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-dynamic-vs-regular-480x99.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Both the regular campaign (top) and DSA campaign (bottom) are struggling due to competing over the same traffic.</em></p>
<p>The easiest way to apply negatives is through <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/06/06/negative-keyword-guide">negative keyword lists</a>, which is why I suggest making DSA their own campaigns. Negative keyword lists can‚Äôt be applied at the campaign level only. If you choose to keep DSA in the same campaign, be sure you <strong>add all keywords you‚Äôre actively bidding on as exact match negatives</strong>.</p>
<p>A final note on DSA: it is critical that you‚Äôve <strong>set negative targets</strong>. This ensures your DSA doesn‚Äôt waste budget going to the homepage or blog content.</p>
<p>Ad extensions can also help provide reasonable coverage for lower profit parts of the business without actively investing marketing dollars. <strong>Use sitelinks, callouts, price extensions, and structured snippets to cover low search volume or expensive keyword concepts.</strong> This will ensure your budget isn‚Äôt being set up to fail while also boosting the CTR for your ads.</p>
<p>As you work through your account structure, you‚Äôll be able to identify which parts are aligned and which ones need to be adjusted.</p>
<h3>Takeaways:</h3>
<ul>
<li>If you don‚Äôt have budget for all parts of your business, consider using extensions or DSA to cover them.</li>
<li>Overstuffed campaigns with too many objectives will flounder. Check for number of ad groups/keywords, locations targeted, and products/services being covered by a campaign.</li>
<li>Check for campaign/ad group level negatives and if negative keyword lists are being used, ensure there aren‚Äôt missing ad group level negatives (to direct traffic).</li>
</ul>
<h2>2. Do you trust your conversion tracking?</h2>
<p>Conversion tracking is a crucial part of PPC campaigns. Yet it‚Äôs also one of the easiest things to mess up (<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/05/24/google-ads-conversion-tracking">conversion tracking hangups here</a>). When auditing campaigns, it can be easy to fall into false positives/negatives due to bad conversion tracking.</p>
<p>The first and more important check is establishing that conversion tracking is set up and tracking actions your business finds valuable. To do this, go to Tools &amp; Settings &gt; Conversions.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-conversions.png" alt="google ads - how to access conversions from tools and settings" width="720" height="377" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-61103" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-conversions.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-conversions-480x251.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>There, you‚Äôll be able to see which actions are set as primary vs secondary conversion actions.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-conversion-actions.png" alt="primary conversion actions in google ads" width="720" height="487" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-61107" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-conversion-actions.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-conversion-actions-480x325.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Primary actions will count towards recorded <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/cost-per-action">cost per acquisition</a> (CPA) and act as a signal for bidding. Secondary actions will be noted but will not influence reporting or bidding algorithms.</p>
<p>It‚Äôs crucial to ensure the right actions are being tracked and that they‚Äôre designated correctly.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-submit-lead-forms-goal.png" alt="ppc audit - goal edit view in google ads" width="720" height="483" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-61104" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-submit-lead-forms-goal.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/ppc-audit-submit-lead-forms-goal-480x322.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>For phone leads, it‚Äôs also important that you‚Äôre not double-counting conversions with call tracking technology. If you use a call tracking solution, odds are you have an analytics goal for that, and should stick with it as the primary tracking. Google call tracking is useful for call-only ads and extensions if you don‚Äôt have any other form of tracking for your site.</p>
<p>Finally, it‚Äôs crucial to check that there isn‚Äôt duplicate code. Many tools and channels require their own tracking snippet. Make sure your sites don‚Äôt have duplicate google tag manager (GTM) on them or tracking hard coded into the header and in GTM. You can check this by using Google Tag Assistant or pressing ctrl/command u to see source code.</p>
<h3>Takeaways:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Make sure the right conversion actions are set to primary.</li>
<li>Confirm there are no instances of duplicate code.</li>
<li>If phone leads are important, make sure to use some form of call tracking.</li>
</ul>
<h2>3. How well does your copy/creative match your target persona?</h2>
<p>Ad accounts are more than structure and bids. A big part of their success is on the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/01/03/ad-copy-examples">ad copy</a> and creative and how well it is predisposed to land with the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/11/target-audience">targeted audience</a>.</p>
<p>As you‚Äôre auditing your account, it‚Äôs important to check for two critical points:</p>
<ul>
<li>Is the copy/creative speaking to the unique market demands of the ad group?</li>
<li>Are audiences being used as targets/exclusions to prequalify budget?</li>
</ul>
<p>As a general rule of thumb, you only want <strong>one major creative idea per ad group</strong> (still allowing for A/B tests). If you‚Äôre combining too many products/services/personas into one ad group, you won‚Äôt be able to speak directly to customer needs, eroding the effectiveness of the creative.</p>
<p>This is especially true with responsive search ads (RSAs), which inherently enable A/B testing on copy/creative.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/how-responsive-search-ads-work.png" alt="how responsive search ads work" width="720" height="481" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-59791" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/how-responsive-search-ads-work.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/how-responsive-search-ads-work-480x321.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><strong>Make sure you‚Äôve pinned your ‚Äúhooks‚Äù to headline one (H1), and your calls-to-action (CTA) to headline two (H2)</strong>. Headline three doesn‚Äôt always show so that should only be used for ‚Äúnice to have‚Äù creative. You can find more tips in this <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/05/responsive-search-ad-copy">responsive search ad copy template</a>.</p>
<p>Be sure to check for audiences (targeted and excluded). If your campaign is using a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/12/19/google-ads-automated-bidding">Smart Bidding strategy</a>, any Observe bid adjustments will be ignored. It‚Äôs good to check for them just in case you are expecting to focus budget towards or away from specific audiences. <strong>Directional audiences should always be on Target and Observe</strong> (or excluded if they‚Äôre not ideal).</p>
<h3>Takeaways:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Message map creative so there‚Äôs one buyer persona per ad group.</li>
<li>If you‚Äôre using smart bidding, confirm observation audiences don‚Äôt have bid adjustments.</li>
<li>Save your best creative for headlines one and two in RSAs.</li>
</ul>
<h2>4. Are you falling into accidental waste?</h2>
<p>Important disclaimer: Ad platforms do not have malicious intent and ultimately are invested in helping brands/advertisers succeed.</p>
<p>There are certain settings that are very easy to enable‚Äîand also miss opting out of‚Äîthat can lead to accidental waste. These settings fall under both manual and automated strategies.</p>
<p><strong>One of the biggest settings to look out for is location options.</strong> When you<a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/07/07/google-ads-geotargeting"> target a location</a>, it can be targeting people in + people who show interest in the location, only people in the location, or only people who show interest.</p>
<p>The default is to target everything, which can lead to spend outside the targeted area. Be sure that you check every campaigns‚Äô settings and confirm the location options are correct.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/google-ads-geotargeting-location-options-presence-interest.png" alt="google ads location targeting - location options" width="500" height="241" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-51042" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/google-ads-geotargeting-location-options-presence-interest.png 500w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/12/google-ads-geotargeting-location-options-presence-interest-480x231.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Another slightly insidious bit of waste comes from a mostly helpful part of Google Ads: the Keyword Planner. It‚Äôs very easy to accidentally add in a lot of broad keywords to one ad group, as opposed to getting keyword concepts to add to multiple ad groups on the correct match type.</p>
<p>Be sure you‚Äôre <strong>adding keywords that won‚Äôt be accidental duplicates</strong> or put you in auctions you don‚Äôt value/can‚Äôt afford.</p>
<h3>Takeaways:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Confirm your location settings are correct.</li>
<li>Make sure keyword suggestions are being added on the correct match-type and to the right place.</li>
</ul>
<h2>5. Should you be scaling or optimizing?</h2>
<p>Many <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/07/06/ppc-account-audit">PPC audits</a> are focused on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/08/24/google-ads-optimization">optimizing account performance</a> (i.e. eliminating wasted spend). Yet understanding signs of success and scale are equally important.</p>
<p><a href="https://localiq.com/blog/what-is-impression-share/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Impression share</a> is a great metric to help you understand where the account is and where it could be. If your impression share is low due to rank, that likely means there are structural issues getting in the way of ROI. Impression share lost to budget points to even more potential profit (so long as business operations can support additional volume).</p>
<p>Another great indicator for optimization vs scale is your click-through rate (CTR) to conversion rate. If your CTR and conversion rate are high, that means you can take that proven method and apply to other markets/add budget into the campaign. If the CTR or conversion rates are low, you know you have a creative or targeting issue (and should remain in optimization mode).</p>
<h3>Takeaways:</h3>
<ul>
<li>Use impression share to guide you on whether you‚Äôre in optimization or scale mode.</li>
<li>Always check in with sales and CS to confirm you can handle more business.</li>
<li>If CTR and Conversion rates are both good, you have winning creative and targeting.</li>
</ul>
<h2></h2>
<h2>Ask these questions in every PPC account audit</h2>
<p>PPC audits are never a one-and-done process. Be sure you‚Äôre constantly asking these questions of your account and holding true to the business metrics you need to succeed:</p>
<ol>
<li>Does your account structure support your business goals?</li>
<li>Do you trust your conversion tracking?</li>
<li>How well does your creative match your target persona?</li>
<li>Are you falling into accidental waste?</li>
<li>Should you be scaling or optimizing?</li>
</ol>
<p>Our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/google-adwords?cid=Web_Any_InContentTextLink_PPC_AWGrader_AWGrader">free Google Ads Performance Grader</a> can help with this process, identifying both areas of improvement as well as strong areas to scale. Try it and see what you find! Or reach out to see how our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/marketing-services?cid=Web_WS_InContent_TextLink_Solutions_Marketing_Services_Demo">digital marketing solutions</a> can take care of this process for you!</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/05/16/ppc-audit">The Super-Easy, 5-Question PPC Audit</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
