										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Local Service Ads (LSAs) are a hero channel for local brands looking for more cost-effective leads. This real estate client achieved 10X the ROI than the conventional real estate lead flow:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/local-services-ads-roi-graph.png" alt="google local services ads yield 10x higher ROI than traditional real estate lead flow" width="720" height="599" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-63903 aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/local-services-ads-roi-graph.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/local-services-ads-roi-graph-480x399.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://localiq.com/blog/google-local-services-ads-for-real-estate/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Local Services Ads for real estate</a> = big wins</em></p>
<p>While they are incredibly simple to maintain once set up, they have undergone some changes since they began in 2016, both in how they&#8217;re set up and the markets they work for. So in this post, I&#8217;m going to outline the pitfalls and mechanics to account for, as well as seven tips to get the most out of Google Local Services Ads.</p>
<h2>Local Services Ads 101</h2>
<p>Before getting into the tips, here&#8217;s a brief refresher on Google LSAs. You can learn more in our <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/06/11/google-local-service-ads">Ultimate Guide to Google Local Services Ads</a>, but here are the basics.</p>
<h3>What are Google Local Services Ads?</h3>
<p>Google Local Services Ads are an ad type geared for home service-based businesses. While Google Search Ads are pay per click and <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/ad-ranking">Ad Rank</a> is based on factors like bid, ad quality, and more, LSAs are pay per lead and ad rank is based on factors like <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/07/16/how-to-ask-for-reviews">customer reviews</a>, proximity, and hours. The ads appear above regular Google Search Ads and the advertiser goes through an extensive verification process.</p>
<h3>Types of LSAs</h3>
<p>Google has two versions of LSAs: Google Screened and Google Guaranteed.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Google Screened</strong> is for white-collar industries like real estate, lawyers, and accountants.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-google-screened-real-estate-e1649639391162.png" alt="google local services ad - google screened result" width="719" height="520" class="aligncenter wp-image-60049 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-google-screened-real-estate-e1649639391162.png 719w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-google-screened-real-estate-e1649639391162-480x270.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 719px, 100vw" /></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Google Guaranteed </strong>is for blue-collar industries like plumbing, housekeeping, and locksmiths. The core difference between the programs is Google Guaranteed will protect customers up to $2000 for problems on the job. Google Screened does not have this protection.</li>
</ul>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-local-services-ads-google-guarantee-hvac.png" alt="google local services ads - google guaranteed result" width="719" height="650" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-65107" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-local-services-ads-google-guarantee-hvac.png 719w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/google-local-services-ads-google-guarantee-hvac-480x434.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 719px, 100vw" /></p>
<ul></ul>
<h3>Setting up LSAs</h3>
<p>To qualify for either program, businesses need to meet the following requirements:</p>
<ul>
<li>A minimum 3.0 Google Business Profile rating.</li>
<li>A Google Ads account (potentially an MCC account‚Äîmore on this later).</li>
<li>Background checks for required team members.</li>
</ul>
<p>When setting up your LSA profile you‚Äôll be prompted to set up a review link, as well as input your credentials.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-setup.png" alt="google local services ads - setup checklist" width="720" height="346" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60041" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-setup.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-setup-480x231.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<h2>Google Local Services Ads: 7 tips to improve your ROI</h2>
<p>Google LSAs make it easy for lawyers, real estate agents, and <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-home-service-businesses-can-show-up-for-local-google-searches/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">home services businesses to show up for local searches</a>. Here are some small details that can make a big difference in the ROI of your LSAs.</p>
<h3>1. Know whether to have an MCC vs an individual ad account</h3>
<p class="p1">It‚Äôs always easier to establish <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2017/08/30/facebook-ads-account-structure">account structure</a> from the outset than fixing it later. Understanding whether your brand is best suited for a manager account (MCC) versus an individual ad account comes down to the following considerations:</p>
<ul class="ul1">
<li class="li1"><span class="s1"></span>Do you serve more than one major market?</li>
<li class="li1"><span class="s1"></span>Are you a¬†<a href="https://localiq.com/blog/franchise-marketing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">franchise</a>?</li>
<li class="li1"><span class="s1"></span>Are you an agency?</li>
</ul>
<p class="p1">It‚Äôs a best practice to limit LSA profiles to three major targets per profile. Otherwise, if you serve more than one location, you are diluting the budget focus and potentially risking the proximity ranking factor. Serving multiple locations can benefit from having multiple Google Business Profiles, with one LSA profile per market.</p>
<p class="p1"><strong>Essentially, unless you just target one market, you will need more than one profile.¬†¬†</strong></p>
<p class="p1">Setting up your LSA profiles as an MCC will allow you to easily navigate between them without logging in and out of your account. You‚Äôll also get the benefit of MCC-level billing, reporting, and shared assets.</p>
<p class="p1">As a franchise/agency this is especially important as you only can share login access with a LSA profile with one other email.</p>
<h3>2. Target no more than 3 major markets</h3>
<p>Each Local Services Ads profile should be viewed as a campaign. Just like you wouldn‚Äôt ask a campaign to service more than one major market, it‚Äôs unrealistic to ask a Local Services Ads to target more than three major markets.</p>
<p>So as just mentioned, in an ideal structure, you‚Äôd have each LSA profile focusing on one major market (corresponding to one Google Business Profile).</p>
<p>However if you only have one GBP and serve multiple locations, <strong>be sure the locations you choose to target are in close proximity to your main prospect hubs</strong> (i.e where you‚Äôll have a higher likelihood of benefiting from the proximity ranking factor).</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-service-areas.png" alt="google local services ads - service area selection" width="720" height="604" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60042" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-service-areas.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-service-areas-480x403.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Targeting a county or DMA counts as one target. You can exclude zip codes or towns to narrow your focus and bypass competitive auctions.</p>
<p>While there is no official cap for brands in a given market, the average amount of vendors a given geo can support is 35. It‚Äôs i<strong>mportant to quickly secure your LSA profile and focus budget on priority markets so you can ensure your dominance on the SERP.</strong></p>
<p><strong>RELATED:</strong> <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/10/12/local-seo">10 Local SEO Tips to Dominate the Local SERP</a></p>
<h3>3. Avoid unnecessary disapprovals</h3>
<p>The most common reason for LSAs to stop serving are <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/06/23/google-ads-disapprovals">disapprovals</a>, and two common disapprovals are for the image to get flagged or certifications to go out of date.</p>
<p><strong>To avoid expired certifications:</strong></p>
<p>When you‚Äôre setting up your profile you‚Äôll be asked to input the expiration date of your certifications. However, some certifications don‚Äôt need to be renewed‚Äîor if they do, they‚Äôre not an annual renewal. Be sure to set the expiration date far enough in advance that you won‚Äôt need to think about it for 5-10 years.</p>
<p><strong>To avoid flagged headshots:</strong></p>
<p>For your headshot, it‚Äôs important that your picture is of more than just your face. <strong>Ideal images will cover down to the elbows.</strong> Here is an example of a headshot that will likely succeed:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-image.png" alt="google local services ads - image" width="500" height="502" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60036" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-image.png 500w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-image-480x482.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 500px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Here is an example of a headshot that will likely fail:</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-image-approval.png" alt="google local services ads - acceptable headshot" width="416" height="389" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60037" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-image-approval.png 416w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-image-approval-300x281.png 300w" sizes="(max-width: 416px) 100vw, 416px" /></p>
<p>Profile pictures don‚Äôt need to have a plain white background or lack personality. The core difference between one being acceptable and the other not is the visibility of the arms.</p>
<h3>4. Keep your Google reviews up</h3>
<p><span>Keep in mind that reviews on your regular Google Business Profile appear on your LSA profile and impact your ad ranking, but not the other way around. And any reviews you get from your LSAs will go away if you stop advertising, and you won‚Äôt be able to respond to reviews that come through your review link.¬†</span></p>
<p>It&#8217;s also important to know that¬†Local Service Ads require a 3.0 average review rating to remain active. If your Google Business Profile slips below 3.0, your ads will stop serving till your review score clears 3.0.</p>
<p>You can learn <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/09/16/get-more-google-reviews">how to get more Google reviews here</a>. And make sure your Google Business Profile and other <a href="https://localiq.com/products/listings/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">directories</a> are accurate and updated with this <a href="https://localiq.com/free-business-listings-grader/?utm_source=wordstream&amp;utm_medium=blog&amp;utm_campaign=freemium" target="_blank" rel="noopener">free business listings grader</a>.</p>
<h3>5. Set higher bids and budgets</h3>
<p>It‚Äôs understandable that brands might be wary of setting aggressive bids and budgets on a new marketing channel. Local Service Ads invite the pitfall of underbudgeting and bidding because of their reputation for <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/07/30/cost-effective-ad-types">low-cost leads.</a></p>
<p>When you set up your campaigns, you‚Äôre given the option to set a manual bid per lead or opt into <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2018/12/19/google-ads-automated-bidding">automated bidding</a>. It‚Äôs common for ads to under-serve (or not serve at all) if you opt into auto bidding with a low budget.</p>
<p><strong>As a general rule, you typically want to set a budget 2-3 times what you actually plan on spending</strong> as Google often struggles to spend the budget. So if the goal is to spend $5,000 per month, you‚Äôd want to set a budget at $15,000.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-budget-overview.png" alt="google local services ads - budget overview" width="720" height="214" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60040" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-budget-overview.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-budget-overview-480x143.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em>Though the budget for this account was set to $10,000, Google only spent $3,054.</em></p>
<p><strong>Also, the cap per bid has gone up to $1,000,¬† </strong>so if you‚Äôre struggling to gain traction with auto bidding, you might be running into competitors setting aggressive manual bids. This might be a reason to target a tangential market.</p>
<p>Because you only pay for calls lasting at least two minutes or form fills, your marketing dollars are going to have a much easier conversion rate than <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/paid-search">traditional paid search</a> (which requires you to pay per click). If your leads cost $50 and you have a goal of $500 monthly spend, that means you‚Äôre striving for 10 leads per month. Depending on your bandwidth, you might want to strive for more or less leads.</p>
<h3>6. Set realistic hours</h3>
<p><a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/08/19/conversion-rate-benchmarks">Conversion rates</a> for LSAs and response times have a strong correlation: the faster you are to respond to leads, the greater the chance you will win the business.</p>
<p>Local Service Ads do not factor response times into ranking, but they do learn what kind of users result in successful calls/form-fills.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-hours.png" alt="google local services ads - business hours view" width="557" height="623" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60043" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-hours.png 557w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-hours-480x537.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 557px, 100vw" /></p>
<p><strong>Make sure your LSA is set to only run when you have the team to respond. </strong>If you can‚Äôt support leads 24/7, do not let the campaign run 24/7. This will help Google allocate budget as efficiently as possible.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-job-types.png" alt="google local services ads - job types" width="720" height="551" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60035" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-job-types.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-job-types-480x367.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h3>7. Mark your leads</h3>
<p>If a lead turns into business, mark it as closed successfully, and archive leads that aren‚Äôt a good fit. Some lead quality issues can be because of services you said you were open to taking (i.e., saying you‚Äôll take rentals but you really only do sales/purchases), but most will be because the prospect just wasn‚Äôt right. Archiving the lead communicates that to Google so it can learn where not to invest your budget.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-leads-view.png" alt="google local services ads - leads view" width="720" height="528" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-60038" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-leads-view.png 720w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/04/google-local-services-ads-leads-view-480x352.png 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 720px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>Follow these tips to succeed with Google LSAs</h2>
<p>Local businesses can‚Äôt afford to leave Local Service Ads out of their <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/12/15/local-marketing-ideas">local marketing efforts</a>. Thankfully they‚Äôre easy to maintain and the performance pitfalls are easy to bypass. Just be sure to follow these seven tips:</p>
<ol>
<li>Know whether to have an MCC vs an individual ad account.</li>
<li>Target three markets or less per LSA profile.</li>
<li>Set your certification expiration dates far out in advance and make sure profile images show down to the elbows.</li>
<li>Maintain your review threshold.</li>
<li>Budget 2-3x higher than what you actually plan on spending.</li>
<li>Set your hours only to the times in which you&#8217;re available to respond quickly.</li>
<li>Mark your leads whens successful and archive those that aren&#8217;t a good fit.</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
